fields.description:
When quota enforcement extension is used with EIAM to limit the number of instances to run, there are a few things that are incorrect:

[Policy]

{code}
# euare-accountgetpolicy -a hspencer -p vm-limit
{
  "Version":"2011-04-01",
  "Statement":[{
    "Sid":"4",
    "Effect":"Limit",
    "Action":"ec2:RunInstances",
    "Resource":"*",
    "Condition":{
      "NumericLessThanEquals":{
        "ec2:quota-vminstancenumber":"3"
      }
    }
  }]
}
{code}

1) We allow the user to run more than the amount defined in the policy when the user uses the "-n" flag with euca-run-instances.

{code}
# euca-run-instances -k test-3admin1 -n 5 emi-45333CB6
RESERVATION	r-C3F14029	374066492507	default
INSTANCE	i-42C742F7	emi-45333CB6	0.0.0.0	0.0.0.0	pending	test-3admin1	0		m1.small	2012-06-13T21:28:10.445Z	PARTI00	eki-E71F3B00	eri-400B394B
INSTANCE	i-C17A41A6	emi-45333CB6	0.0.0.0	0.0.0.0	pending	test-3admin1	1		m1.small	2012-06-13T21:28:10.467Z	PARTI00	eki-E71F3B00	eri-400B394B
INSTANCE	i-2DB04295	emi-45333CB6	0.0.0.0	0.0.0.0	pending	test-3admin1	2		m1.small	2012-06-13T21:28:10.48Z	PARTI00	eki-E71F3B00	eri-400B394B
INSTANCE	i-9AD53FB4	emi-45333CB6	0.0.0.0	0.0.0.0	pending	test-3admin1	3		m1.small	2012-06-13T21:28:10.493Z	PARTI00	eki-E71F3B00	eri-400B394B
INSTANCE	i-CEF443E4	emi-45333CB6	0.0.0.0	0.0.0.0	pending	test-3admin1	4		m1.small	2012-06-13T21:28:10.507Z	PARTI00	eki-E71F3B00	eri-400B394B
{code}

2) The behavior is correct (from what I have seen) that the number of instances that gets into the running state (when using euca-run-instances -n) matches what is defined in the policy.  The others stay in pending state. IMO, we should not allow user to run more than defined in the policy:

{code}
# euca-describe-instances 
RESERVATION	r-C3F14029	374066492507	default
INSTANCE	i-2DB04295	emi-45333CB6	192.168.46.207	10.174.36.218	pending	test-3admin1	2		m1.small	2012-06-13T21:28:10.48Z	PARTI00	eki-E71F3B00	eri-400B394B
INSTANCE	i-42C742F7	emi-45333CB6	192.168.46.205	10.174.36.208	pending	test-3admin1	0		m1.small	2012-06-13T21:28:10.445Z	PARTI00	eki-E71F3B00	eri-400B394B
INSTANCE	i-9AD53FB4	emi-45333CB6	192.168.46.208	10.174.36.209	running	test-3admin1	3		m1.small	2012-06-13T21:28:10.493Z	PARTI00	eki-E71F3B00	eri-400B394B
INSTANCE	i-C17A41A6	emi-45333CB6	192.168.46.206	10.174.36.203	running	test-3admin1	1		m1.small	2012-06-13T21:28:10.467Z	PARTI00	eki-E71F3B00	eri-400B394B
INSTANCE	i-CEF443E4	emi-45333CB6	192.168.46.209	10.174.36.207	running	test-3admin1	4		m1.small	2012-06-13T21:28:10.507Z	PARTI00	eki-E71F3B00	eri-400B394B
{code}

3) When we error out when the user passes the amount defined in the policy, we should error out with the leftover resources of the entire cloud. (This behavior happens when euca-run-instances is used with/without -n)

{code}
# euca-run-instances -k test-3admin1 emi-45333CB6
RunInstancesType: Not enough resources (28 in PARTI00 < 1): vm instances.
{code}

comments.body:
In a 3.0.2 setup on CentOS6, I had this quota policy to "support" account

{code}
{
"Statement":[{
   "Effect":"Limit",
   "Action":"ec2:RunInstances",
   "Resource":"*",
   "Condition":{
     "NumericLessThanEquals":{
       "ec2:quota-vminstancenumber":"2"
     }
   }
 }]
}
{code}

The user within the "support" account had a policy as well (this is a IAM policy, basically restricting him to only m1.small, m1.large and c1.medium instance types and allowing certain other stuff):

{code}
{
 "Statement":[{
  "Effect":"Allow",
  "Action":"*",
  "Resource":[
    "arn:aws:ec2:::vmtype/m1.small",
    "arn:aws:ec2:::vmtype/c1.medium",
    "arn:aws:ec2:::vmtype/m1.large",
    "arn:aws:ec2:::image/*",
    "arn:aws:ec2:::securitygroup/*",
    "arn:aws:ec2:::keypair/*",
    "arn:aws:ec2:::instance/*",
    "arn:aws:ec2:::availabilityzone/*",
    "arn:aws:ec2:::volume/*",
    "arn:aws:ec2:::snapshot/*"
  ]
  }
 ]
}
{code}

When the user ("deependra") in "support" account starts 4 VMs using

{code}
euca-run-instances -k sshlogin -n 4 emi-A7EA3A66
{code}

All VMs have started successfully and shows as "running". The user can as well login to them using SSH.

{code}
euca-describe-instances 
RESERVATION	r-859D400B	363863921415	default
INSTANCE	i-1A8E456B	emi-A7EA3A66	192.168.61.2	10.10.109.28	running	sshlogin	1		m1.small	2012-06-14T02:35:41Z	jeevan-cluster	eki-B5FC3BF2	eri-24E83B9B
INSTANCE	i-6D0D40C1	emi-A7EA3A66	192.168.61.3	10.10.109.29	running	sshlogin	2		m1.small	2012-06-14T02:35:41Z	jeevan-cluster	eki-B5FC3BF2	eri-24E83B9B
INSTANCE	i-9E4842A1	emi-A7EA3A66	192.168.61.1	10.10.109.26	running	sshlogin	0		m1.small	2012-06-14T02:35:41Z	jeevan-cluster	eki-B5FC3BF2	eri-24E83B9B
INSTANCE	i-C1144238	emi-A7EA3A66	192.168.61.4	10.10.109.25	running	sshlogin	3		m1.small	2012-06-14T02:35:41Z	jeevan-cluster	eki-B5FC3BF2	eri-24E83B9B
{code}

This sounds different from what Harold has observed though.

Let me know if there are any questions.

Cheers!
Deependra
